{
  "texts": [
    "These processes are known as the forward and reverse processes, respectively.",
    "In this section, we provide a brief overview of the original SGMs in [17], which will be adapted for the time-series generation tasks.1) Forward and Reverse Process: At first, SGMs add noises with the following stochastic differential equation (SDE):dx s = f(s, x s)ds + g(s)dw, s ∈ [0, 1],where w ∈ R dim(x) is a multi-dimensional Brownian motion, f(s, •): R dim(x) → R dim(x) is a vector-valued drift term, and g: [0, 1] → R is a scalar-valued diffusion function.",
    "Hereafter, we define x s as a noisy sample diffused at time s ∈ [0, 1] from an original sample x ∈ R dim(x).",
    "Therefore, x s can be understood as a stochastic process following the SDE.There are several options for f and g: variance exploding(VE), variance preserving(VP), and subVP.",
    "It is proved that VE and VP are continuous generalizations of the two discrete diffusion methods [17]: NCSN and DDPM in [18], [19]."
  ]
}